         <abstract resp="pers:SB2">
            <p>A bilingual two-stanza poem in manuscript in Eaton’s fonds, this composition also appears in
               <ref target="doc:HonorableMissMoonlight1"><title level="m">The Honorable Miss Moonlight</title></ref> in which it is sung by the Spider to Moonlight’s baby. Eaton’s
               poem bears a passing resemblance to traditional Japanese lullabies attributed to
               specific regions: The traditional Chūgoku region lullaby repeats the word <foreign xml:lang="ja">Nenneko</foreign>
               (meaning <q>hushabye</q>) and the brevity of Eaton’s piece recalls the six-line traditional Edo
               lullaby. Inspired by such pieces, Eaton appears to have amalgamated and re-interpreted their
               stylistic attributes in a manner that reflects the characteristic synthesis of Western and Eastern
               cultures in her early oeuvre, as is evinced in her alternation between Japanese and
               English.</p>
         </abstract>
